ch graphs, transfer operators |\ndocs/milestones.md:481:## Milestone 6 — Construct surface discretizations and operators\ndocs/milestones.md:500:- fine-to-coarse transfer operators\ndocs/milestones.md:534:Turn connectome edges into transfers between neuron surface states.\ndocs/milestones.md:559:- deciding how synaptic transfer modifies the surface state  \ndocs/milestones.md:565:- the simulator knows where and how input transfers between neurons  \ndocs/milestones.md:1113:- operator implementation support for Milestone 6  \ndocs/milestones.md:1118:- Milestone 6  \ndocs/milestones.md:1230:- transfer operators  \ndocs/milestones.md:1305:6. Milestone 6  \ntests/test_operator_contract.py:80:            Path(\"/tmp/flywire_wave_fixture/101_transfer_operators.npz\"),\ndocs/geometry_descriptor_qa.md:9:Milestone 6 operator work and Milestone 11 hybrid-morphology work have a shared\ndocs/geometry_descriptor_qa.md:65:Milestone 6 will likely add operator-aware checks such as Laplacian-spectrum\ndocs/geometry_descriptor_qa.md:66:drift, geodesic path distortion, or transfer-operator residuals. Milestone 11\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:1:# Milestone 6 Surface Discretization Tickets\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:10:## FW-M6-001 - Freeze a versioned operator bundle contract and discretization design note\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:13:- Source: Milestone 6 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:17:Milestone 5 produces geometry bundles that are useful preprocessing artifacts, but they are not yet a stable numerical-operator contract. The repo has no canonical definition for which operator family is being used, which auxiliary matrices and geometry fields must be serialized, how boundary handling is represented, or how downstream code should discover coarse-versus-fine transfer structures. Without a versioned contract and an explicit design note, later simulator work will bind itself to ad hoc archive keys and undocumented mathematical assumptions.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:20:Define a first-class operator bundle contract for Milestone 6 and document the numerical design choices behind it. The implementation should centralize artifact naming and metadata in library code, extend the processed manifest so downstream consumers can discover operator assets without hardcoded filenames, and add a markdown design note that compares the viable discretization families before committing to the default. The design note should be decisive: pick the default fine-surface discretization, explain when fallback behavior is allowed, state which quantities should be conserved or damped, and record the stability-relevant assumptions the later wave engine will inherit.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:24:- The processed manifest records an explicit operator-contract version plus per-root metadata for discretization family, normalization or mass treatment, boundary-condition mode, geodesic-neighborhood settings, and transfer-operator availability.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:36:## FW-M6-002 - Assemble fine-surface operators with geodesic neighborhoods, tangent frames, and boundary masks\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:39:- Source: Milestone 6 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:43:The current processed surface graph is still a Milestone 5 scaffold. It exposes simplified mesh connectivity and a uniform graph Laplacian, but it does not yet provide the numerical objects Milestone 6 actually needs: geodesic neighborhoods, boundary masks, local tangent frames, metric-aware weights, or a surface operator whose supporting geometry is explicit enough to debug and validate. That leaves the repo unable to build a simulation-ready single-neuron surface state without rewriting the existing graph archive by hand.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:46:Implement the fine-surface operator builder that turns a simplified mesh bundle into a numerically meaningful fine-resolution operator artifact. Use the discretization family chosen in `FW-M6-001`, and serialize the supporting geometry needed to inspect or reuse the operator later: adjacency and edge geometry, local areas or mass terms, normals and tangent frames, geodesic-neighborhood structures, and boundary masks. Keep sparse assembly in library code, make the script layer an orchestrator only, and ensure the output is deterministic for the same mesh and config.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:60:Assume `FW-M6-001` is already in place. Favor inspectable sparse formats and explicit metadata over opaque archives that require reverse-engineering at read time.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:62:## FW-M6-003 - Construct coarse patch operators and fine-to-coarse transfer operators that stay consistent with the fine surface\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:65:- Source: Milestone 6 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:66:- Area: coarse operators / transfer maps / multiresolution numerics\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:69:Milestone 5's patch graph is a useful coarse partition, but it is still only a topological summary. There is no formally defined restriction or prolongation operator, no coarse mass treatment, and no guarantee that the coarse patch dynamics are meaningfully derived from the fine surface discretization rather than just sharing a vaguely similar graph shape. Without transfer operators and consistency checks, the repo cannot compare coarse and fine evolution honestly.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:72:Build the coarse operator layer as a real multiresolution discretization derived from the fine surface operator. Introduce fine-to-coarse and coarse-to-fine transfer operators, define the coarse operator assembly rule, serialize the mass or area terms needed for the coarse state, and emit comparison metrics that quantify how well coarse application matches fine application after transfer. The implementation should make it easy for later simulator code to project states between resolutions without reconstructing the math from raw patch-membership arrays.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:75:- The processed operator bundle includes first-class transfer-operator artifacts or arrays in addition to the coarse patch operator itself.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:76:- The coarse operator is derived through a documented scheme tied to the fine discretization, rather than being assembled through an unrelated ad hoc graph rule.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:78:- The build step emits coarse-versus-fine comparison metrics such as transfer residuals, Rayleigh-quotient drift, or another documented quality measure appropriate to the chosen discretization.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:79:- Regression coverage validates deterministic transfer construction, patch coverage assumptions, and coarse-versus-fine consistency on local fixture assets.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:83:- A focused fixture test that builds fine and coarse operators together, applies transfer in both directions, and asserts the documented consistency tolerances\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:86:Assume `FW-M6-001` and `FW-M6-002` have landed. The core requirement is not just having a patch graph; it is having a coarse model that downstream code can trust as a principled reduction of the fine one.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:88:## FW-M6-004 - Add configurable boundary-condition and anisotropy plumbing to operator assembly\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:91:- Source: Milestone 6 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:95:The roadmap explicitly calls for boundary masks and optional anisotropy tensors, but the current pipeline has no stable way to describe or assemble either. If Milestone 6 ships only a hardcoded isotropic operator with implicit boundary behavior, Milestones 10 and 13 will have to reopen the asset contract and retroactively guess how directional propagation or boundary semantics were supposed to work.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:114:## FW-M6-005 - Ship operator quality metrics, pulse-propagation smoke tests, and offline inspection tooling\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:117:- Source: Milestone 6 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:121:Milestone 6 is only complete if the team can initialize a pulse on one neuron, verify that surface propagation behaves stably enough for later engine work, compare coarse and fine operators quantitatively, and inspect the results without digging through raw arrays. Right now there is no standard harness that exercises those numerical behaviors, no operator quality report, and no offline visualization flow for reviewing what the assembled operators are actually doing on the mesh.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:124:Add a Milestone 6 validation and inspection workflow that consumes local operator bundles and produces actionable diagnostics. The workflow should initialize localized test fields, run a lightweight stability-oriented evolution or repeated operator application suitable for pre-engine validation, compute operator quality metrics, and generate an offline report that overlays relevant outputs on the mesh and patch decomposition. The goal is not to build the final wave engine; it is to make operator quality, pulse localization, and coarse-versus-fine behavior inspectable and regression-testable before Milestone 10 begins.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:138:Assume the earlier Milestone 6 tickets have already landed. Favor lightweight offline artifacts such as Markdown plus images, HTML, or another review-friendly format that can be attached to run logs without special infrastructure.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:140:## FW-M6-006 - Run a Milestone 6 implementation verification pass and publish a readiness report\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:143:- Source: Milestone 6 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:147:Even if the Milestone 6 build tickets land individually, the repo still needs one explicit follow-up pass that verifies the pieces work together as a coherent operator pipeline. Without a dedicated implementation-verification ticket, it is too easy to stop at local success on isolated subtasks while leaving behind contract drift, missing docs, broken report paths, weak regression coverage, or untested assumptions between fine operators, coarse operators, transfer maps, and QA tooling.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:150:Perform a senior-level verification pass over the completed Milestone 6 implementation and publish a concise readiness report in-repo. This pass should exercise the full operator pipeline on fixture assets and at least one realistic local bundle, confirm that documentation matches the shipped behavior, identify any mismatches or scientific risks, and either close them directly or record them as follow-on issues. Treat this as an integration and audit ticket rather than a net-new feature ticket.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:153:- The full Milestone 6 workflow is executed end-to-end using the shipped commands and local assets, with results captured in a deterministic report location.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:154:- The verification pass checks contract compatibility across geometry assets, fine operators, coarse operators, transfer operators, boundary handling, anisotropy settings, and QA report generation.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:155:- The readiness report summarizes what was verified, what remains risky or deferred, and whether Milestone 6 is ready to support Milestone 10 engine work.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:161:- `python3 scripts/run_agent_tickets.py --tickets-file agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md --ticket-id FW-M6-006 --dry-run`\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:165:This ticket should run after the earlier Milestone 6 tickets are complete. The main deliverable is confidence: one place where a reviewer can see that the milestone is integrated, documented, and ready for downstream simulator work.\nscripts/06_operator_qa.py:20:        description=\"Generate an offline operator QA report from local Milestone 6 bundles.\"\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:57:- the coarse operator archive stores patch mass / area, Galerkin-projected stiffness, the mass-normalized coarse operator, and the quality metrics used to compare coarse and fine application\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:58:- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_transfer_operators.npz` stores explicit fine/coarse transfer structure, physical-field restriction / prolongation matrices, normalized-state transfer operators, and transfer-quality metrics\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:59:- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_operator_metadata.json` records the realized discretization family, fallback mode, versioned `operator_assembly` config, boundary mode, anisotropy model, geodesic-neighborhood settings, transfer availability, coarse assembly rule, and coarse-versus-fine quality metrics for downstream discovery\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:82:- `docs/operator_bundle_design.md` is the authoritative Milestone 6 operator\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:88:Milestone 6 also now defines one deterministic offline inspection workflow for\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:91:- `scripts/06_operator_qa.py` reads the local fine operator, coarse operator,\ndocs/pipeline_notes.md:92:  transfer bundle, patch graph, and operator metadata for one or more root IDs\ntests/fixtures/operator_metadata_fixture.json:50:  \"transfer_operators\": {\ntests/fixtures/operator_metadata_fixture.json:53:      \"path\": \"/tmp/flywire_wave_fixture/101_transfer_operators.npz\",\ntests/fixtures/operator_metadata_fixture.json:58:      \"path\": \"/tmp/flywire_wave_fixture/101_transfer_operators.npz\",\ntests/fixtures/operator_metadata_fixture.json:64:      \"path\": \"/tmp/flywire_wave_fixture/101_transfer_operators.npz\",\ntests/fixtures/operator_metadata_fixture.json:82:    \"transfer_operators\": {\ntests/fixtures/operator_metadata_fixture.json:83:      \"path\": \"/tmp/flywire_wave_fixture/101_transfer_operators.npz\",\ndocs/operator_qa.md:3:Milestone 6 is not finished when bundles merely serialize. Before Milestone 10\ndocs/operator_qa.md:20:- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_transfer_operators.npz`\ndocs/operator_qa.md:87:- fine and coarse operator symmetry residuals\ndocs/operator_qa.md:91:  the transfer bundle\ndocs/operator_qa.md:155:  decomposition and transfer quality before deciding whether the bundle is still\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T185349Z/FW-M6-006_Run_a_Milestone_6_implementation_verification_pass_and_publish_a_readiness_report/stdout.jsonl:4:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I’m treating this as an integration audit: first I’m locating the Milestone 6 pipeline, its docs, and any existing verification hooks so I can run the shipped workflow before changing anything.\"}}\nsrc/flywire_wave/operator_qa.py:79:    \"transfer_gal